  <lemma xml:id="lecture-notes-lem-ac-method">
    <title>Using the <m>ac</m>-Method to Solve a Quadratic Equation</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> be a quadratic function.
        If there are factors of the product <m>ac</m> that add to <m>b</m>, we can factor this trinomial and use the Zero Product Property to solve for <m>x</m>.
        Here is how to check if we can factor using this method.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>Compute the product <m>ac</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>List all the factors of the product. You are looking for one of two things:
            <ul>
              <li><p>If <m>c &gt; 0</m>, find two numbers whose sum equals <m>b</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p>If <m>c &lt; 0</m>, find two numbers whose difference equals <m>b</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p>If you cannot find such a pair, you cannot use this method.</p></li>
            </ul>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li><p>Suppose you find factors <m>d</m> and <m>e</m> such that <m>de = ac</m> and <m>d + e = b</m>. Then replace <m>bx</m> with <m>dx + ex</m> to get <m>ax^2 + dx + ex + c = 0</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Use Factor by Grouping to solve the equation.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </lemma>

