  <lemma xml:id="lecture-notes-lem-completing-the-square-traditional-method">
    <title>Completing the Square (Traditional Method)</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> with <m>a \ne 0</m> and <m>b \ne 0</m>.
        Follow the steps below to complete the square.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>Move <m>c</m> to the other side of the equation to get <m>ax^2 + bx = -c</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Divide each term by the leading coefficient <m>a</m> to get <m>x^2 + \frac{b}{a}x = -\frac{c}{a}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Divide <m>\frac{b}{a}</m> by 2 to get <m>\frac{b}{2a}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Compute <m>\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 = \frac{b^2}{4a^2}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Add <m>\frac{b^2}{4a^2}</m> to both sides of the equation.</p></li>
          <li><p>
            The left-hand side is now a perfect square trinomial and can be factored as
            <m>\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2</m>. The equation becomes
            <m>\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 = -\frac{c}{a} + \frac{b^2}{4a^2}</m>.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>Use the Square Root Property to solve for <m>x</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </lemma>

